definition.value: Catalysis of the reaction -  di-trans, octa-cis-undecaprenol + ATP -eq- di-trans,octa-cis-undecaprenyl phosphate + ADP + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction -  ethylnitronate + FMNH(2) + O(2) -eq- acetaldehyde + FMN + H(2)O + H(+) + nitrite.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently and non-covalently with a polymer of ubiquitin formed by linkages between lysine residues at position 48 of the ubiquitin monomers.
An Isw1 complex that binds DNA and has nucleosome-stimulated ATPase activity. In S. cerevisiae, contains an Isw1p ATPase subunit in complex with Ioc3p.
An Isw1 complex that binds DNA and has nucleosome-stimulated ATPase activity. In S. cerevisiae, contains an Isw1p ATPase subunit in complex with Ioc2p and Ioc4p.
Catalysis of the reaction -  glycerol 3-phosphate + NADP+ -eq- glycerone phosphate + H+ + NADPH.
Catalysis of the reaction -  acetyl-CoA + H2O + oxaloacetate -eq- citrate + CoA.
Catalysis of the reaction -  (R)-pantolactone + NADP+ -eq- 2-dehydropantolactone + NADPH + H+.
Catalysis of the transfer of protons from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  ATP + H2O + H+(in) --gt- ADP + phosphate + H+(out).
Catalysis of the reaction -  3'-phosphoadenylyl sulfate + dermatan -eq- adenosine 3',5'-bisphosphate + dermatan 6'-sulfate.
The end of a microtubule that does not preferentially grow (polymerize).
An endosomal sorting complex required for transport.
An RNA interference where the silencing signal spreads along the target mRNA in a 5' or 3' direction, outside of the initial target sequence.
A protein complex that has growth factor activity.
Catalysis of the transfer of a iron-sulfur cluster from one compound (donor) to another (acceptor).
Catalysis of the reaction -  L-methionine (S)-S-oxide + thioredoxin --gt- L-methionine + thioredoxin disulfide + H2O.
A cytoplasmic, non-membrane bound granule of, at least, keratinocyte. Associated to keratin intermediate filaments and partially crosslinked to the cell envelope.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a hepatocyte growth factor.
Catalysis of the thiol-dependent hydrolysis of an ester, thioester, amide, peptide or isopeptide bond formed by the C-terminal glycine of ubiquitin.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a BLOC-2 complex, a protein complex required for the biogenesis of specialized organelles of the endosomal-lysosomal system, such as melanosomes and platelet dense granules.

Combining with the ligand TRAIL (tumor necrosis factor-related apoptosis-inducing ligand) and transmitting the signal from one side of the plasma membrane to the other to initiate apoptotic cell death.
A ribonucleoprotein granule located in the cytoplasm.
Catalysis of the reaction -  5-hydroxy-L-tryptophan + H+ -eq- CO2 + serotonin.
Catalysis of the reaction -  L-dopa + H+ -eq- CO2 + dopamine.
Catalysis of the reaction -  L-tryptophan + H+ -eq- CO2 + tryptamine.
Interacts with and increases tyrosine 3-monooxygenase (tyrosine hydroxylase) activity.
The region of a neuron that includes the cell body (cell soma) and the dendrite, but excludes the axon.
Interacts with and increases L-dopa decarboxylase activity.
Interacts with, and stops, prevents or reduces the activity of a peroxidase.
Interacts with, and stops, prevents or reduces the activity of nitric oxide synthase.
A heterodimeric protein complex that is composed of the transcription factor CHOP (GADD153) and a member of the C|EBP family of transcription factors.

label.value: epidermal growth factor receptor ligand maturation

definition.value: Any process leading to the attainment of the full functional capacity of a ligand for an epidermal growth factor receptor. The ligand is functional when it can bind to and activate an epidermal growth factor receptor.

label.value: peptide bond cleavage involved in epidermal growth factor receptor ligand maturation

definition.value: The hydrolysis of a peptide bond or bonds within a ligand for the epidermal growth factor receptor, as part of protein maturation, the process leading to the attainment of the full functional capacity of a protein. In Drosophila for example, in the Golgi apparatus of the signal producing cell, Spitz is cleaved within its transmembrane domain to release a functional soluble extracellular fragment.

label.value: netrin receptor activity involved in chemoattraction

definition.value: Combining with a netrin signal and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to contribute to the directed movement of a motile cell towards a higher concentration of netrin.
Combining with the fat-cell specific hormone leptin and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity.

Combining with an odorant and transmitting the signal across the membrane by activating an associated G-protein -  promotes the exchange of GDP for GTP on the alpha subunit of a heterotrimeric G-protein complex.

Receiving a signal and transmitting the signal in the cell to initiate a change in cell activity. A signal is a physical entity or change in state that is used to transfer information in order to trigger a response.
Combining selectively with an extracellular macromolecule and delivering the macromolecule into the cell via endocytosis.
Combining with the secreted glycoprotein reelin, and transmitting the signal from one side of the membrane to the other to initiate a change in cell activity.
Combining with the sphingolipid sphingosine-1-phosphate (S1P), and transmitting the signal across the membrane by activating an associated G-protein.
A protein complex that contains two G-protein coupled receptors.

A protein complex that contains two G-protein coupled receptors (GPCRs) of the same subtype. Formation of a GPCR homodimer may be important for the transport of newly formed receptors to the cell surface, and the function of the receptor.
A protein complex that contains two G-protein coupled receptors (GPCRs) of different subtypes. Formation of a GPCR heterodimer may alter the functional property of the GPCR.

label.value: large latent transforming growth factor-beta complex

definition.value: A protein complex containing latency-associated proteins (LAPs), mature disulphide-linked dimeric TGF-beta, and latent TGF-beta binding proteins (LTBPs). TGF-beta is mostly secreted as part of the large latent complex, and must be subsequently released from the LLC in order to bind to cell surface receptors.

Combining with an enkephalin, and transmitting the signal across the membrane by activating an associated G-protein. A enkephalin is a pentapeptide (Tyr-Gly-Gly-Phe-Met or Tyr-Gly-Gly-Phe-Leu) involved in regulating nociception in the body.
Combining with morphine (17-methyl-7,8-didehydro-4,5alpha-epoxymorphinan-3,6alpha-diol), and transmitting the signal across the membrane by activating an associated G-protein.

Combining with a dynorphin peptide, and transmitting the signal across the membrane by activating an associated G-protein. Dynorphin is any opioid peptide that is generated by cleavage of the precursor protein prodynorphin.

label.value: ligand-activated RNA polymerase II transcription factor binding transcription factor activity

definition.value: Combining with a signal and transmitting the signal to the transcriptional machinery by interacting selectively and non-covalently with an RNA polymerase II transcription factor, which may be a single protein or a complex, in order to modulate transcription. For example, some steroid hormone receptors bind to transcription factor complexes to regulate transcription of genes whose promoters do not contain hormone response elements.

label.value: glucocorticoid-activated sequence-specific DNA binding RNA polymerase II transcription factor activity

definition.value: Combining with a glucocorticoid and transmitting the signal to the transcriptional machinery by interacting selectively and non-covalently with a specific DNA sequence in order to modulate transcription by RNA polymerase II.

label.value: glucocorticoid-activated RNA polymerase II transcription factor binding transcription factor activity

definition.value: Combining with a glucocorticoid and transmitting the signal to the transcriptional machinery by interacting selectively and non-covalently with an RNA polymerase II transcription factor, which may be a single protein or a complex, in order to modulate transcription. For example, glucocorticoid-bound receptors can bind to transcription factor complexes to regulate transcription of genes whose promoters do not contain glucocorticoid response elements.
